We utilize the formal model of verifying UFDI attacks, as
described in our previous work [11, 24], for evaluating the
efficacy of our proposed MTD mechanism. Here, we briefly
describe this verification model for readers' convenience.
We define cj to denote whether state j (1 ≤ j ≤ n) is affected
(i.e., changed to an incorrect value) due to false data
injection. Note that, in the DC model, each state corresponds
to a bus. Thus, n is equal to b. The attacker may
not be able to alter a measurement due to inaccessibility or
existing security measures. We define ri to denote whether
measurement i is accessible to the attacker. We also define
si to denote whether the measurement is secured or not.
A.1
Formalization of Attacks on States
The attack on state j specifies that the voltage phase angle
at bus j is changed. This condition is formalized as follows:
∀1≤j≤n cj → (Δθj = 0)
From Equation (1), it is obvious that a change of PiL is
